        {
          "anchor" : "How-to-Identify-a-Series-Circuit",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "How to Identify a Series Circuit",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "If a component’s terminal is connected to (and ONLY to) the terminal of one other component, then the two",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "components are in series. Note that in larger circuits, a “component” may be, say, a parallel circuit. The",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "“component” would then be in series with other components, but other components would not be in series with",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "the “component”’s components.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Power-in-a-Series-Circuit",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Power in a Series Circuit",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "The power dissipated in a series circuit is the sum of the power dissipated in each component. Mathematically,",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "P = P_1 + P_2 + \\ldots + P_n",
            "= \\sum_{i=1}^{n} I^2 R_i"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "where",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "$P$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is the total power",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "$I$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is the current through the circuit (assumed to be the same for all components in series)",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "$P_i$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is the power dissipated in component ",
                      "type" : "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "code" : "$i$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : ".",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "$R_i$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is the resistance of component ",
                      "type" : "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "code" : "$i$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : ".",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Kirchhoffs-Voltage-Law-Application",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Kirchhoff’s Voltage Law Application",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Kirchhoff’s voltage law states that the sum of the potential differences across all components in a closed",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "loop is equal to 0. A series circuit is a closed loop, so the sum of the potential differences across all",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "components in a series circuit is equal to the voltage supplied by the source.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Note about the application of ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$V=IR$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " to do with KVL: If you have a voltage ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$V_{AB}$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " from point ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$A$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " to point ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$B$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : ":",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "If current flows from ",
                      "type" : "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "code" : "$A$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " to ",
                      "type" : "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "code" : "$B$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : ", then ",
                      "type" : "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "code" : "$V_{AB}$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is positive (ie ",
                      "type" : "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "code" : "$V_A>V_B$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : ")",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "If current flows from ",
                      "type" : "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "code" : "$B$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " to ",
                      "type" : "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "code" : "$A$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : ", then ",
                      "type" : "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "code" : "$V_{AB}$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is negative (ie ",
                      "type" : "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "code" : "$V_A<V_B$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : ")",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "When applyind KVL, you need to be very careful about the signs of the voltages.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Voltage-Notation",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Voltage Notation",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "A single subscript notation is used to indicate the potential at a point in the circuit. For example,",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$V_A$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " indicates the potential at point ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$A$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : ".",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "A double subscript notation is used to indicate the potential difference between two points in the circuit. For example,",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$V_{AB}$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " indicates the potential difference between points ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$A$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " and ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$B$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : ". It is also defined as:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "V_{AB} = V_A - V_B"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "If ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$V_{AB}$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " is positive, point ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$A$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " is at a higher potential than point ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$B$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : ".",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Voltage-Symbols",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Voltage Symbols",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "A “ground component” represents a 0V potential. All grounds in a circuit are taken to be connected - a",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "series circuit where the battery’s negative terminal is connected to ground and the component’s negative",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "terminal is connected to ground is equivalent to a series circuit where the battery’s negative terminal is",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "connected to the component’s negative terminal.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "A battery symbol represents a voltage source. The positive terminal (voltage is usually referred to as ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$V_ {CC}$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : ") of the battery is connected to the longer line of the symbol, and the negative terminal (voltage is",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "usually 0) is connected to the shorter line of the symbol. You can imagine it like charge “flowing” from the",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "longer line to the shorter line.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "There is a component known as a “DC voltage source”. They are a circle with a “+” and “-” sign inside, so",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "its quite obvious which side is which.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "An “ideal voltage source” has a constant voltage level, and no resistance. Most batteries are not ideal",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "because they lose voltage as they discharge, and have a small internal resistance.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "kind" : "content"
    }
  ],
